 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 be the set of invertible 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 lower triangular matrices.
 Show:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}L_{2}\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1},L_{2}\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}^{-1}\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $L\in\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A lower triangular matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is invertible if and only if the diagonal has no zero entry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The product 
\begin_inset Formula $A=LDU$
\end_inset

 is unique if it exists (
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular, 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is diagonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 have ones on the diagonal).
\end_layout

